{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536746"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15807"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15807"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.03,0.01,0.06,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8498"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86683"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37325"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman is returned to the hospital ward following the insertion of an internal jugular central venous catheter. Shortly after returning from the procedure, an urgent review is requested due to sudden onset shortness of breath. She has a medical history of breast cancer and is currently undergoing chemotherapy. She does not take any regular medications apart from her chemotherapy regimen and antiemetics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed and is using her accessory muscles of respiration. Her pulse rate is 110/min and regular, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is not elevated. Heart sounds are dual with no murmurs or added sounds. There are decreased breath sounds on the right side. The central line insertion site appears clean and dry, with small amounts of ooze.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography pulmonary angiogram","Transthoracic echocardiogram","Electrocardiogram","Doppler ultrasound of the central venous catheter","Chest X-ray"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation in this scenario. The patient has developed sudden onset dyspnoea and hypoxaemia with unilateral decreased breath sounds following central venous catheter insertion, raising strong suspicion for pneumothorax. Chest X-ray is the quickest and most accessible imaging modality to confirm the diagnosis and guide further management, such as the need for intercostal catheter insertion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing pulmonary embolism, but this is less likely given the immediate temporal relationship to the procedure and the presence of unilateral chest signs. It is not the first-line investigation in this context and would delay the diagnosis and management of pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E transthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for assessing cardiac tamponade or other cardiac complications, but the absence of elevated jugular venous pressure, muffled heart sounds, or hypotension makes this less likely. It is not the most appropriate initial investigation for acute respiratory distress with unilateral chest findings after central line insertion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E electrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may be performed to assess for arrhythmias or cardiac ischaemia, but it does not provide information about pneumothorax or other structural lung pathology. It would not be the investigation of choice in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoppler ultrasound of the central venous catheter\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess for deep vein thrombosis or vascular injury but would not identify a pneumothorax or explain the acute respiratory findings. It is not indicated in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chest X-ray is the investigation of choice for suspected pneumothorax following central venous catheter insertion.","Prompt imaging is essential to confirm diagnosis and guide management in patients with acute respiratory distress after central line placement.","Other investigations may be indicated depending on clinical suspicion, but should not delay immediate assessment for pneumothorax."],"references":["Tsotsolis N, Tsirgogianni K, Kioumis I, Pitsiou G, Baka S, Papaiwannou A, Karavergou A, Rapti A, Trakada G, Katsikogiannis N, Tsakiridis K, Karapantzos I, Karapantzou C, Barbetakis N, Zissimopoulos A, Kuhajda I, Andjelkovic D, Zarogoulidis K, Zarogoulidis P. Pneumothorax as a complication of central venous catheter insertion. Ann Transl Med. 2015 Mar;3(3):40. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2305-5839.2015.02.11. PMID: 25815301; PMCID: PMC4356862."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15807"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86683"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-01T10:34:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-01T10:36:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8498"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attribu